DESCRIPTION:

This program is a basic server and client messaging project developed and tested in Python 3.8.3. The client and server are 
fully contained within ttweetcl.py and ttweetsrv.py respectively. Upon the initialization of the server via ttweetsrv.py, 
clients can be initialized via the ttweetcl.py file in individual terminal given that the correct port and server IP address 
is used. All required Python packages can be installed if necessary, via the regular process used in most Python projects.

At the time of writing, the program features seven standard commands that are executable form the client side which have behavior 
implications on both the server and client sides of the application. These commands are: tweet, subscribe, unsubscribe, timeline, 
getusers, gettweets, and exit. The server maintains dictionary for each user which includes hashtags they are subscribed to as 
well as previous messages that they have tweeted. This information is available for access by all client-facing users through 
the appropriate commands. Each client maintains a list of all received messages which are also displayable if the client requests it. 

Upon a tweet message each client will either receive the message if they are subscribed to the appropriate hashtag or a notification 
message implying that the message will not be sent to that specific client in order to move on with prompting the user for input. 
Additionally, several other scenarios require the server to indicate to the client that an invalid input has been provided which is 
possible thanks to special key phrases that are only interpreted in the backend of the client and cannot be sent as input from it. 
Appropriate error messages will be displayed on the client side in order to inform the user about the error. 

This architecture has been designed with future scalability in mind and can be used as a basis for larger scale projects with a wider array 
of client and/or server functionality. Note that debug output is displayed on the server-facing side of the application.Thanks to parallel processing 
being integrated into the application with thread locks in order to restrict which command the client is currently processing, the server is able 
to maintain an unlimited number of clients as long as the host device that the server is running has sufficient memory and hardware capabilities.

#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
COMPILING INSTRUCTIONS:

1. - open terminal in project folder location

2. - run python server file (ttweetsrv.py) on python 3.x.x to initalize python server 
     (Ex: $python ttweetsrv.py 13000)

3. - open a second terminal in project folder location 

4. - run python client file (ttweetcl.py) on python 3.x.x to initalize a python client 
     (Ex: $python ttweetcl.py 127.0.0.1 13000 John)

5. - Upon successfull initialization of client (initialization message will be shown 
     on server and client terminal) the client and server are communicating and the client can now execute commands.

#----------------------------------------------------------------------------------
BUGS / LIMITATIONS / NOTES:

- Note: If the user submits nothing and simply presses the Enter key it will move to the next line and prompt for new input.
- Note: Certain commands will paste output (or nothing depending on circumstance) and skip a line before prompting for new input.
- LIMITATIONS: This application does not work due to OS specific code on Unix based machines.
- Note: This software was built and tested on Python version 3.8.3 64-bit Windows x86.

